","footnotes":"false","disclaimer":"false","relatedContent":"false","metrics":"true"},"keywords":[{"type":"IEEE Keywords","kwd":["Social network services","Protocols","Mobile communication","Mobile computing","Servers","Privacy","Cryptography"]},{"type":"INSPEC: Controlled Indexing","kwd":["mobile computing","security of data","social networking (online)"]},{"type":"INSPEC: Non-Controlled Indexing","kwd":["secure friend discovery","mobile social networks","physical vicinity","privacy concerns","protocols","potential attacks","secure proximity estimation","potential friend discovery","privacy-preserving manner","verifiability","smartphones"]}],"formulaStrippedArticleTitle":"Secure friend discovery in mobile social networks","allowComments":false,"pubLink":"/xpl/conhome/5888673/proceeding","abstract":"Mobile social networks extend social networks in the cyberspace into the real world by allowing mobile users to discover and interact with existing and potential friends who happen to be in their physical vicinity. Despite their promise to enable many exciting applications, serious security and privacy concerns have hindered wide adoption of these networks. To address these concerns, in this paper we develop novel techniques and protocols to compute social proximity between two users to discover potential friends, which is an essential task for mobile social networks.We make three major contributions. First, we identify a range of potential attacks against friend discovery by analyzing real traces. Second, we develop a novel solution for secure proximity estimation, which allows users to identify potential friends by computing social proximity in a privacy-preserving manner. A distinctive feature of our solution is that it provides both privacy and verifiability, which are frequently at odds in secure multiparty computation. Third, we demonstrate the feasibility and effectiveness of our approaches using real implementation on smartphones and show it is efficient in terms of both computation time and power consumption.","issueLink":"/xpl/tocresult.jsp?isnumber=5934870","doiLink":"https://doi.org/10.1109/INFCOM.2011.5934958","doi":"10.1109/INFCOM.2011.5934958","startPage":"1647","endPage":"1655","pdfPath":"/iel5/5888673/5934870/05934958.pdf","rightsLink":"http://s100.copyright.com/AppDispatchServlet?publisherName=ieee&publication=proceedings&title=Secure+friend+discovery+in+mobile+social+networks&isbn=978-1-4244-9919-9&publicationDate=April+2011&author=Wei+Dong&ContentID=10.1109/INFCOM.2011.5934958&orderBeanReset=true&startPage=1647&endPage=1655&proceedingName=2011+Proceedings+IEEE+INFOCOM","displayPublicationTitle":"2011 Proceedings IEEE INFOCOM","publicationTitle":"2011 Proceedings IEEE INFOCOM","pdfUrl":"/stamp/stamp.jsp?tp=&arnumber=5934958","isReadingRoomArticle":false,"isGetArticle":false,"isGetAddressInfoCaptured":false,"isMarketingOptIn":false,"pubTopics":[{"name":"Computing and Processing"},{"name":"Communication, Networking and Broadcast Technologies"},{"name":"Components, Circuits, Devices and Systems"}],"publisher":"IEEE","xploreDocumentType":"Conference Publication","isNotDynamicOrStatic":false,"isCustomDenial":false,"isSMPTE":false,"isOUP":false,"isSAE":false,"isNow":false,"isPromo":false,"chronOrPublicationDate":"10-15 April 2011","htmlAbstractLink":"/document/5934958/","displayDocTitle":"Secure friend discovery in mobile social networks","isStandard":false,"conferenceDate":"10-15 April 2011","persistentLink":"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/servlet/opac?punumber=5888673","isConference":true,"isProduct":false,"isMorganClaypool":false,"isEarlyAccess":false,"accessionNumber":"12085751","isOpenAccess":false,"isEphemera":false,"publicationDate":"April 2011","dateOfInsertion":"30 June 2011","htmlLink":"/document/5934958/","isChapter":false,"isStaticHtml":true,"isJournal":false,"isBook":false,"isBookWithoutChapters":false,"isFreeDocument":false,"isDynamicHtml":true,"startPage":"1647","openAccessFlag":"F","ephemeraFlag":"false","